England":"Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Franceis","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Francis  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Francis","meanings":["English: from the Old French personal name <i>Franceis</i>, modern French <i>François</i>, from Latin <i>Franciscus</i>, originally ‘Frank’, though later used to denote a Frenchman. The personal name owed much of its popularity during the Middle Ages to the fame of Saint Francis of Assisi (1181–1226), whose baptismal name was actually <i>Giovanni</i> but who was nicknamed <i>Francisco</i> because his father was absent in France at the time of his birth. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages, e.g. Italian   Francesco   and Polish, Czech, Slovak, Slovenian, and Croatian   Franc  , and also their derivatives, e.g. Croatian <b>Francišković</b> (see   Francisco   4).","English: ethnic name from the Old French adjective <i>Franceis</i> ‘French’ (see 1 above).","Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames, or an adoption of the non-Jewish surname."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert de Franceis I was born in 1152, in Surrey, England, his father, Sir Thomas II de Hurst Baron Franceis, was 28 and his mother, Agnes de Hurst, was 26. He married Isabella de Bretton in 1170, in England. They were the parents of at least 5 sons. He died in 1170, in Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 18."},"et":{"1152–1170":"1152–1170","–Male":"Surnud","1154–1170":"1154–1170","1170–1210":"1170–1210","1175–Male":"1175–Surnud","1177–Male":"1177–Surnud","1182–Male":"1182–Surnud","1124–1152":"1124–1152","1126–1152":"1126–1152","1126":"1126","1124":"1124","1177":"1177","1210":"1210","1154":"1154","1175":"1175","1152":"1152","1182":"1182","1170":"1170","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Horsley, Surrey, England":"Surrey, England","Horsley Hall, Surrey, England":"East Horsley, Surrey, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Osmondeston, Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1152–1170":"1152–1170","–Male":"Kuollut","1154–1170":"1154–1170","1170–1210":"1170–1210"